Czech discovery: a substance which works on 'hardy' viruses HIV
A team of Czech and German scientists testing the new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of enhanced substance is that it works and the viruses that have won against drugs immunity.
This fact is , in some cases , that the compound to a normal variant of the virus is not as strongly as some already available medicines .
The disease AIDS still cannot be cured.
However, patients can significantly extended the life of a combination of drugs that prevent the virus replication of HIV in the body.
Their use, however, is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Partial suppression of propagation of the virus has also resulted in the development of the so-called resistentních viruses against which the drugs are ineffective.
The work of experts from the three institutes of the Academy of Sciences, Institute of Chemical Technology in Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with resistance to the virus.
Proved that a substance called metalokarborany acts on a protein responsible for the reproduction of HIV.
Metalokarborany are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds are blocking the spread of the virus otherwise than all today used drugs, and therefore may overcome the problem of resistance.
In his work, scientists have come with the new 'improved' compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to viral protein.
Metalokarborany a unique three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages formed by atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon atom are linked metal, in this case cobalt.
Treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is a protein of HIV, which is necessary for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV proteázou caused by the fission of HIV would not ripe infectious virus particles.
If we stop HIV proteázu, and stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the researchers explain in a press release issued by the Institute of organic chemistry and biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In work published in the scientific journal Journal of the medicinal Chemistry scientists describe a series of compounds, in which they are two pairs of cages (see table) interconnected short organic chain, which is also systematically revised.
A slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of anti HIV protease was tested in vitro and also against the resistant (resistant) variants derived from patients infected with HIV.
The effect of the variant of the enzyme to normal metalokarboranů is not as strong as that of clinically used drugs, but its effect does not for resistant variants against which are used drugs are often ineffective.
A unique mechanism of action and its other characteristics such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of another chemical treatments of metalokarboranů makes interesting compounds for further research leading to the design of effective drugs against HIV, says Pauline Mobil, head of the lab Structural Biology Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and Molecular Genetics Institute of the Academy of Sciences.
