Philippine militants are still holding back more than 50 people, children released to freedom
Today, militants in the south of the Philippines was kidnapped 75 people, including several of primary school pupils and their teachers.
It said the agency AFP, which initially reported only about 65 hijacked.
All 17 of children was after eight hours released, including one teacher.
The abduction occurred in the province of Agusan del Sur.
About 19 of the armed men allegedly used hostages as a shield during the run from the police.
Local negotiators are now trying to agree on the issue of the remaining hostages.
According to the AFP agency, militants belong to the New People's Army (NPA), which is an armed component of the Communist Party of the Philippines (CPP).
According to the AP police originally kidnapper pursued because of the violence, which has cost a settling of accounts between two local family clans.
In the south of the Philippines in the province of Maguindanao was because of the recent massacre, in which were killed 57 people, declared martial law.
Among the victims of the massacre of 23 November associated with the election to office guvernérského was 30 journalists.
On suspicion of involvement in the massacre was arrested the governor of the province, and his father Andal jihofilipínské Ampatuan, an influential patriarch of the genus Ampatuanů.
On the island of Mindanao are engaged also Muslim separatists.
But on Tuesday renewed his peace talks with the government .
