It may be a Muslim Frenchman?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when the Swiss voters called for a ban on the building and minarets and generally spread alarm reports of alleged Islamization of Europe, John Bowen, an American academic, wrote a brief, whether they are allowed to integrate Muslims - and whether they will integrate - into one of the continent nejotevřenějších secular society.
Some of the readers, after reading this book admirers became the artist's final works, "Why the French do not like scarves on the head" (2006), this elegant and diskutovanou study on the issues that divide and employ the country for over a period of 15 years and whose impact is still felt today.
The last book of Mr Bowen has a broader and much more ambitious in scope.
Like a good anthropologist wants to know not only what the politicians and the media said about Islam in France, but what actually happened in the base.
He spent months in mosques, schools and institutes, which are now taking care of 5 ÷ 6 million French Muslims, which Mr. Bowen called 'Islamic areas'.
Is a good listener, reproduces the debate between teachers and students on issues that most concern.
Should a Muslim enter into matrimony in the mosque or at the town hall (or in both places)?
It should be taught about the development of young Muslim and gay rights?
It may be a Muslim marry a man who is not a Muslim?
He has the right to use of a Muslim zájmově oriented banking system, if it wants to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly mundane issues, which are being discussed, and which are part of everyday life, rather than a political drama, which employ media.
Author identifies a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, among other well-known people, including the Tarik Ramadan, Arab, Muslim scholar and academic, born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open a discussion on how you can simultaneously be a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
They have arguments for all their custom.
The conservatives are suspicious of the actual idei French or European Islam.
Philosophers and activists that Mr Bowen conducted interviews, on the belief that they are the counterpart Selafiho purists — supporters of Sunni Islam, combined in Saudi Arabia — this group is small, but it affects the European Muslims.
Mr. Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism are compatible.
But the adaptation requires compromises on both sides.
It wonders how far they are French politicians (and intellectual elite that so obstinately defends the general public) actually committed to the idea of pluralism.
He is of the view that Muslims are in matters of faith may have less experience than Catholics, Protestants and Jews, who also had to make the historic compromise with secular republikánstvím.
Rather than the development of pragmatism found "tightening the screws values."
It may be a Muslim Frenchman? After reading this book, someone may have a tendency to say "yes, but not now."
Nejbezútěšnější prospects in the world
The Arctic is changing more rapidly than the rest of the planet's environment .
The ice is melting edged an alarming rate, which affects animals and their survival as anywhere else.
The interests of olejářských, plynařských and fishing companies must be focused on new natural water resources, together with diplomats, lawyers and the writers in their wake-up call.
In the book "On thin ice" Richard Ellis, a writer and illustrator, depicts the natural history of the icons of the North, the polar bear.
Familiar with complicated history and the procedures velrybářství describes a long tradition of polar explorers, who tried to seize the white bear.
The meeting of Admiral Nelson with bold čtrnáctiletým boy who fought only with muskets kolbou is actually a myth, but everything else is true.
Young bears, who swam for the bodies of their mothers being killed, they capture and sent to zoos and circuses.
At the beginning of the 20th century was then in a circus tent 75 polar bears.
Even today, the enclosure at the zoo are typically a million times smaller area than the area you have available to adults in the wild. The climate is rarely appropriate: the resident polar bear in Singapore has turned green from algae growing within the hollow hairs of its coat.
