The Cuban government has enveloped the American government contractor, which imported mobile phones and laptops into the country, according to officials from the Foreign Ministry on Saturday.
The supplier, which has not yet been identified, he worked for the company Development Alternatives, Inc., headquartered in Bethesda.
The company is working on projects for the U.S. Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
Consular officials, along with a U.S. interest section in Havana sought access to the boarded, who was arrested on December 5.
Certain charges has not been made public, but according to the Cuban rights may be a Cuban citizen or a stranger imprisoned for almost anything that are designated as "dangerous".
All of the so-called kontrarevolucionářské activities, which include mild protests and critical monographs, raise the risk of imprisonment.
Anti-graffiti and language are considered a serious offences.
In Cuba, there is a young blogující community, led by the popular commentator Yoani Sánchezovou, who often writes about how she and her husband followed and harassed by government agents.
Mrs Sánchezová repeatedly asked for permission to leave the country in order to be able to accept the prize, but was denied permission.
The detention of an American contractor may be the result of the growing tension between the Communist Castrovým brother, the ruling in Cuba, and the Obama administration, which was tracked as a "delaying tactics" in improving relations with the island.
As the first report on the arrest of the New York Times on Friday night.
The new U.S. policy emphasized that if the Cuban government has taken concrete steps, such as the release of political prisoners and create more space for the opposition, the United States take reciprocal steps.
Mobile phones and laptops are allowed in Cuba, even though they are new and sought-after commodity in a country where the average wage of state employees is $15 per month.
The Cuban government has granted an ordinary citizens the right to buy mobile telephones in just this year; these are used mostly for sending messages textovýchg because 15minutový phone call would cost more than one daily wage.
The use of the Internet on the island is mimořádn limited.
It is available in expensive hotels and for their foreign visitors and on certain government přípojkách, such as universities.
The Cubans, who are often want to log on, must notify their names to the government.
Access to many of the Web page is disabled.
American detention in Cuba is a rarity.
Most of a handful of citizens of the US in the prison in Cuba is behind bars for the tresné actions, such as drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbenová, press the section for american interests in Havana.
Mrs Berbenová said that it could not provide more information about the prison.
His arrest and detention were clearly immoral.
Such activities, which would in any other open societies were legitimate - say, a free mobile phones - there is a criminal offence in Cuba, said Miguel Vivanco, director of the group For Human Rights Program, recently published a report on the freedoms in Cuba, titled "New Castro, the same Cuba," as a reference to the installation of Raul Castro as the leader of the country and compensation for the sickly older brother Fidel.
Vivanco said that defendants are often arrested, tried and imprisoned in one day.
He said that any solution would have been more political and that the Cuban government often provokes a negative reaction in the United States, just as the two countries seek to extensive dialogue.
